      "id": "ph_u1",
      "title": "Unit 1: Mechanics",
      "chapters": [
        {
          "id": "ph_u1_c1",
          "title": "Ch 1: Laws of Motion",
          "concept": {
            "title": "Newton's Laws of Motion",
            "latex": true,
            "body": [
              "Newton's **First Law** (Law of Inertia) states that a body remains in a state of rest or uniform motion in a straight line unless acted upon by an external unbalanced force.",
              "Newton's **Second Law** relates force, mass, and acceleration: $$F = ma$$ where $F$ is the net force (N), $m$ is mass (kg), and $a$ is acceleration (m/s²). This is the most widely used law for solving dynamics problems.",
              "Newton's **Third Law** states that for every action there is an equal and opposite reaction: $$\\vec{F}_{AB} = -\\vec{F}_{BA}$$ These action-reaction pairs always act on different bodies, so they never cancel each other out.",
              "Key application — inclined planes: For a frictionless incline at angle $\\theta$, the component of gravity along the incline is $mg\\sin\\theta$, giving acceleration $a = g\\sin\\theta$. The normal force is $N = mg\\cos\\theta$.",
              "Free body diagrams are essential: always resolve forces into perpendicular components before applying $F=ma$ along each axis."
            ],
            "formulas": [
              "$F_{net} = ma$",
              "$a = g\\sin\\theta$ (frictionless incline)",
              "$N = mg\\cos\\theta$ (normal force on incline)",
              "$f = \\mu N$ (friction force)"
            ]
          },
          "questions": [
            {
              "id": "ph_q1",
              "type": "MCQ",
              "latex": true,
              "question": "A body of mass $m$ is placed on a frictionless incline of angle $\\theta$. The acceleration of the body along the incline is:",
              "options": ["$g \\sin\\theta$", "$g \\cos\\theta$", "$g \\tan\\theta$", "$g$"],
              "answer": [0],
              "explanation": "On a frictionless incline, the component of gravity along the surface is $mg\\sin\\theta$, so $a = g\\sin\\theta$."
            },
            {
              "id": "ph_q2",
              "type": "MSQ",
              "latex": true,
              "question": "Which of the following are correct statements about Newton's Third Law? (Select all that apply)",
              "options": [
                "Action and reaction forces act on different bodies",
                "Action and reaction forces are equal in magnitude",
                "Action and reaction forces cancel each other",
                "Action and reaction are opposite in direction"
              ],
              "answer": [0, 1, 3],
              "explanation": "Newton's Third Law: action-reaction pairs act on different bodies, are equal in magnitude and opposite in direction. They do NOT cancel because they act on different bodies."
            },
            {
              "id": "ph_q3",
              "type": "MCQ",
              "latex": true,
              "question": "A force $\\vec{F} = 10\\hat{i} + 5\\hat{j}$ N acts on a 2 kg body. The magnitude of acceleration is:",
              "options": ["$5\\sqrt{5}$ m/s²", "$\\frac{5\\sqrt{5}}{2}$ m/s²", "$10$ m/s²", "$\\frac{15}{2}$ m/s²"],
              "answer": [1],
              "explanation": "$|\\vec{F}| = \\sqrt{10^2+5^2} = 5\\sqrt{5}$ N. $a = F/m = 5\\sqrt{5}/2$ m/s²."
            },
            {
              "id": "ph_q3n",
              "type": "NAT",
              "latex": true,
              "question": "A block of mass $4\\,\\text{kg}$ is pulled by a horizontal force of $20\\,\\text{N}$ on a frictionless surface. Find its acceleration in m/s².",
              "answer": 5,
              "tolerance": 0.1,
              "unit": "m/s²",
              "explanation": "Using $F = ma$: $a = F/m = 20/4 = 5$ m/s²."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "ph_u1_c2",
          "title": "Ch 2: Work, Energy & Power",
          "concept": {
            "title": "Work, Energy & Power",
            "latex": true,
            "body": [
              "Work done by a force is the dot product of force and displacement: $$W = \\vec{F} \\cdot \\vec{d} = |F||d|\\cos\\theta$$ Work is a scalar quantity measured in Joules (J).",
              "Kinetic Energy is the energy possessed by a body due to its motion: $$KE = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2$$ The Work-Energy Theorem states that the net work done on a body equals its change in kinetic energy: $W_{net} = \\Delta KE$.",
              "Conservative forces (gravity, spring/elastic force) do work that is independent of the path taken — only initial and final positions matter. Their work over a closed path is zero. Non-conservative forces (friction, air drag) dissipate energy as heat and depend on the path.",
              "Potential Energy is associated with conservative forces. Gravitational PE: $U = mgh$. Spring PE: $U = \\frac{1}{2}kx^2$.",
              "Power is the rate of doing work: $$P = \\frac{W}{t} = \\vec{F}\\cdot\\vec{v}$$ measured in Watts (W).",
              "Conservation of Mechanical Energy: In the absence of non-conservative forces, total mechanical energy ($KE + PE$) remains constant."
            ],
            "formulas": [
              "$W = \\vec{F}\\cdot\\vec{d} = Fd\\cos\\theta$",
              "$KE = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2$",
              "$U_{gravity} = mgh$",
              "$U_{spring} = \\frac{1}{2}kx^2$",
              "$P = \\frac{W}{t} = Fv$"
            ]
          },
          "questions": [
            {
              "id": "ph_q4",
              "type": "MCQ",
              "latex": true,
              "question": "The work done by a force $\\vec{F}$ over displacement $\\vec{d}$ is given by:",
              "options": ["$|\\vec{F}||\\vec{d}|$", "$\\vec{F} \\times \\vec{d}$", "$\\vec{F} \\cdot \\vec{d}$", "$\\frac{|\\vec{F}|}{|\\vec{d}|}$"],
              "answer": [2],
              "explanation": "Work is the dot product: $W = \\vec{F} \\cdot \\vec{d} = |F||d|\\cos\\theta$."
            },
            {
              "id": "ph_q5",
              "type": "MSQ",
              "latex": true,
              "question": "Which of the following are conservative forces? (Select all that apply)",
              "options": ["Gravitational force", "Friction force", "Spring (elastic) force", "Air drag"],
              "answer": [0, 2],
              "explanation": "Conservative forces (gravity, spring) have work independent of path. Friction and drag are non-conservative."
            },
            {
              "id": "ph_q5n",
              "type": "NAT",
              "latex": true,
              "question": "A $2\\,\\text{kg}$ object moving at $3\\,\\text{m/s}$ speeds up to $5\\,\\text{m/s}$. Find the work done on it (in Joules).",
              "answer": 16,
              "tolerance": 0.5,
              "unit": "J",
              "explanation": "$W = \\Delta KE = \\frac{1}{2}m(v_f^2-v_i^2) = \\frac{1}{2}(2)(25-9) = 16$ J."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "ph_u2",
      "title": "Unit 2: Waves & Optics",
      "chapters": [
        {
          "id": "ph_u2_c1",
          "title": "Ch 3: Wave Motion",
          "concept": {
            "title": "Wave Motion Basics",
            "latex": true,
            "body": [
              "A wave is a disturbance that transfers energy through a medium (or vacuum, for EM waves) without net transport of matter.",
              "A travelling wave can be written as $$y(x,t) = A\\sin(kx - \\omega t)$$ where $A$ is amplitude, $k = 2\\pi/\\lambda$ is the wave number, and $\\omega = 2\\pi f$ is the angular frequency.",
              "Wave speed relates frequency and wavelength: $$v = f\\lambda = \\frac{\\omega}{k}$$",
              "Transverse waves (e.g. light, waves on a string) have particle displacement perpendicular to wave propagation. Longitudinal waves (e.g. sound) have displacement parallel to propagation.",
              "The principle of superposition states that when two or more waves overlap, the resultant displacement is the algebraic sum of individual displacements — this underlies interference and standing waves."
            ],
            "formulas": [
              "$v = f\\lambda$",
              "$\\omega = 2\\pi f$",
              "$k = \\dfrac{2\\pi}{\\lambda}$",
              "$v = \\dfrac{\\omega}{k}$"
            ]
          },
          "questions": [
            {
              "id": "ph_q6",
              "type": "MCQ",
              "latex": true,
              "question": "The equation of a wave is $y = A\\sin(kx - \\omega t)$. The speed of the wave is:",
              "options": ["$\\frac{k}{\\omega}$", "$\\frac{\\omega}{k}$", "$k\\omega$", "$\\frac{1}{k\\omega}$"],
              "answer": [1],
              "explanation": "Wave speed $v = \\frac{\\omega}{k} = f\\lambda$."
            },
            {
              "id": "ph_q6n",
              "type": "NAT",
              "latex": true,
              "question": "A wave has frequency $50\\,\\text{Hz}$ and wavelength $4\\,\\text{m}$. Find its speed (in m/s).",
              "answer": 200,
              "tolerance": 1,
              "unit": "m/s",
              "explanation": "$v = f\\lambda = 50 \\times 4 = 200$ m/s."
            },
